You will be given a summary of an image (originally derived from a
vision-model description). Rewrite it as a retrieval-only description: a
dense, answer-voice passage that a vector index can match against
natural-language questions about what the image shows.

Principles:
- Answer voice. Write as if answering a question about what is in the
  image, what the scene depicts, what objects or text are present. Do not
  describe the image-as-image. No "this image shows", "the picture
  depicts", "we see". Start with content, not framing.
- Question-implied structure. Every sentence should plausibly answer a
  reader question: what is the subject, where is the scene set, what are
  the key visual elements, what text appears.
- Preserve any visible text verbatim (signage, captions, labels), any
  identifiable named entities (logos, brand names, people if recognizable),
  and any specific numeric or spatial details when they fit naturally.
- 80 to 140 words. Hard floor 50, hard ceiling 180. Images often have less
  content than text sources, so floor and ceiling are lower.
- Single block of prose. No headings, no bullets, no markdown.

Return only the description. No preamble, no commentary, no code fences.

